# Mermaid Diagrams as Code

## Conventions

- Default the orientation to top-down (`TD`/`TB`), not left-right (`LR`). Most screen sizes are too narrow, so `LR` constrains the render to be too small and unreadable; top-down is generally not height-constrained. Escape hatch: use `LR` only when explicitly requested, or when a graph is genuinely wide-and-shallow such that top-down would be worse.
- Use `<br/>` for line breaks in node labels and titles ‚Äî literal `\n` does not render in Mermaid.
- Newest `-beta` and recently added types (e.g. Swimlanes, `architecture-beta`, `radar`) may not render in every host, including Notion ‚Äî verify rendering before relying on them.
- Always include a title via frontmatter, e.g.:

  ```mermaid
  ---
  title: Example Flow
  ---
  flowchart TD
      A[Start] --> B[End]
  ```

## Choosing a diagram type

Pick the type from the question the diagram must answer. Default to the most
specific fit, not the most familiar (`flowchart`). Common lesson: for system
interactions and call flows, a `sequenceDiagram` beats a `flowchart`; when the
key question is *who owns each step*, prefer a swimlane diagram.

### Process & interaction

| Type | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `flowchart` | Branching logic, decisions, and algorithms ‚Äî "what happens next?" with conditional paths. Avoid when actor ownership or message ordering matters. |
| `sequenceDiagram` | Ordered messages between participants over time ‚Äî "who calls whom, in what order." Best for request/response, API/protocol, and distributed call flows (incl. high-level architecture flows). |
| Swimlanes | A process divided by responsibility ‚Äî "who owns each step?" Approval flows, support/delivery processes, any work that crosses teams or systems. |
| `stateDiagram-v2` | Lifecycle of a single entity through states and transitions ‚Äî status machines. |
| `journey` | Steps a user takes with a satisfaction rating per step ‚Äî UX flows. |

### Structure & data

| Type | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `classDiagram` | Static structure: types, attributes, and relationships ‚Äî OOP/domain models. |
| `erDiagram` | Data model: entities, attributes, and cardinality ‚Äî database schema design. |
| `architecture-beta` | Cloud/service infrastructure: services, groups, and their connections ‚Äî system topology. |
| `C4Context` / `C4Container` / `C4Component` | Software architecture at context/container/component levels. |
| `block-beta` | Arbitrary fixed-layout block diagrams when other types don't fit. |
| `treemap` | Nested proportional hierarchy ‚Äî relative sizes within a tree. |
| `mindmap` | Hierarchical brainstorming / idea trees. |

### Time & planning

| Type | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `gantt` | Project schedule: tasks, durations, and dependencies over a timeline. |
| `timeline` | Chronological events ‚Äî history or roadmap. |
| `kanban` | Work items across workflow columns/status. |
| `gitGraph` | Branch/commit/merge history. |

### Quantitative

| Type | Use when |
| --- | --- |
| `pie` | Proportions of a single whole. |
| `xychart-beta` | Numeric series as bars/lines over an axis. |
| `quadrantChart` | Items plotted on two axes (e.g., effort vs. impact). |
| `sankey-beta` | Magnitude of flow between nodes (traffic, budget, energy). |
| `radar` | Compare multiple metrics across categories. |

### None of these fit?

If no type above answers the question, consult the Mermaid diagram-syntax docs
for the full, current type list and syntax: <https://mermaid.js.org/intro/> (the
left sidebar lists every diagram type). Prototype and confirm it renders in the
live editor before committing: <https://mermaid.live>.
